    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Amblyosyllis formosa</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_1955",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Members of this genus are very spectacular and unusual worms, easily identified to genus level by their triangular body segments, very long and coiled dorsal cirri and the elongate, thin, and coiled pharynx, which is thought to be used to pierce pieces of food. Local specimens are usually pink to yellow with distinctive groups of small black lines on the dorsal surfaces of each segment.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_1956",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Body length up to 20 mm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_1957",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> North East Atlantic, Mediterranean, South Africa, Madagascar, Australia, Japan.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> About Saldanha to Cape Agulhas.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_1958",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Very distinctive and attractive, but rarely seen, species that is always a thrill to find and photograph. Usually found singly, crawling actively and rapidly under boulders, or on surfaces of rocks on pools. Also found in kelp holdfasts. The elongate dorsal cirri and extremely mobile and are alternately rolled up tightly and then extended, particularly when the worm is disturbed.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_1959",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Some species in the genus have been observed feeding on sponges.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_1960",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Not known locally, but in North American species sexes are separate and specialised reproductive individuals develop that have large eyes and posterior segments filled with gametes. Eggs are laid in gelatinous masses, which are brooded by the females and develop into crawling juveniles without any free-living larval stages.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_1961",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Unmistakable to genus level, but species within the genus are poorly defined. The World Register of Marine Species currently recognises 10 species, but several of these are widespread and probably represent species complexes. Recent studies (see reference below) have shown considerable morphological and genetic differences between specimens from different sites, but unfortunately no South African material was included in these studies. Pending further work, we thus use the currently-applied name but this may change in the future.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_1962",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Aguado, MT, Capa, M, Lago-Barcia, D, Gil, J, Pleijel, F & Nygren, A (2019). Species delimitation in Amblyosyllis (Annelida, Syllidae).<i>PloS one</i>, 14(4), e0214211.<br><br>Branch, G & Branch M (1981). The Living shores of southern Africa. C. Struik Publishers Cape Town (p. 169, pl. 50).<br><br>Day, JH (1967). A Monograph on the Polychaeta of Southern Africa. British Museum (Natural History), London Part 1 (p. 259).<br><br>Pernet, B (1998). Benthic egg masses and larval development of Amblyosyllis speciosa (Polychaeta: Syllidae). <i>Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom</i>, 78(4), 1369-1372.",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_1963",
